   77  
   78: Web benchmarks are compiled from the same entry point in `lib/web_benchmarks.dart`.
   79  

   81  
   82: Create a new file for your benchmark under `lib/src/web`. See `bench_draw_rect.dart`
   83  as an example.

   87  - A "raw benchmark" records performance metrics from direct interactions with
   88:   `dart:ui` with no framework. This kind of benchmark is good for benchmarking
   89    low-level engine primitives, such as layer, picture, and semantics performance.

   99  For a raw benchmark extend `RawRecorder` (tip: you can start by copying
  100: `bench_draw_rect.dart`).
  101  
  102  For a widget benchmark extend `WidgetRecorder` (tip: you can start by copying
  103: `bench_simple_lazy_text_scroll.dart`).
  104  
  105  For a widget build benchmark extend `WidgetBuildRecorder` (tip: you can start by copying
  106: `bench_build_material_checkbox.dart`).
  107  
  108  Pick a unique benchmark name and class name and add it to the `benchmarks` list
  109: in `lib/web_benchmarks.dart`.
  110  

  124  # Runs in profile mode using the HTML renderer
  125: flutter run --web-renderer=html --profile -d web-server lib/web_benchmarks.dart
  126  
  127  # Runs in profile mode using the CanvasKit renderer
  128: flutter run --web-renderer=canvaskit --profile -d web-server lib/web_benchmarks.dart
  129  ```

  136  # Runs using the HTML renderer
  137: ../../bin/cache/dart-sdk/bin/dart bin/run.dart -t bin/tasks/web_benchmarks_html.dart
  138  
  139  # Runs using the CanvasKit renderer
  140: ../../bin/cache/dart-sdk/bin/dart bin/run.dart -t bin/tasks/web_benchmarks_canvaskit.dart
  141  ```

  17      ffi.Pointer<ffi.Void>, ffi.IntPtr, ffi.Int32, ffi.Int32, ffi.Int32, ffi.IntPtr);
  18: typedef DartMmap = ffi.Pointer<ffi.Void> Function(
  19      ffi.Pointer<ffi.Void>, int, int, int, int, int);
  20: final DartMmap mmap = ffi.DynamicLibrary.process().lookupFunction<CMmap, DartMmap>('mmap');
  21  

  24  typedef CMprotect = ffi.Int32 Function(ffi.Pointer<ffi.Void>, ffi.IntPtr, ffi.Int32);
  25: typedef DartMprotect = int Function(ffi.Pointer<ffi.Void>, int, int);
  26: final DartMprotect mprotect = ffi.DynamicLibrary.process()
  27:     .lookupFunction<CMprotect, DartMprotect>('mprotect');

  179  
  180: A test is a simple Dart program that lives under `bin/tasks` and uses
  181: `package:flutter_devicelab/framework/framework.dart` to define and run a _task_.

  209

  211  service protocol. This ensures that tasks do not interfere with each other and

  229:   file in `bin/tasks` without the `.dart` extension.
  230  - `{DESCRIPTION}` is the plain English description of your test that helps

.fvm/flutter_sdk/dev/docs/README.md:
  26  of the core Flutter framework and are imported using
  27: `'package:flutter/<library>.dart'`, like so:
  28  
  29: ```dart
  30: import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
  31: import 'package:flutter/services.dart';
  32  ```
  33  
  34: #### Dart Libraries
  35  
  36: Libraries in the "Dart" section exist in the `dart:` namespace and are imported
  37: using `'dart:<library>'`, like so:
  38  
  39: ```dart
  40: import 'dart:async';
  41: import 'dart:ui';
  42  ```
  43  
  44: Except for `'dart:core'`, you must import a Dart library before you can use it.
  45  

  49  They are organized by package and are imported using
  50: `'package:<package>/<library>.dart'`, like so:
  51  
  52: ```dart
  53: import 'package:flutter_test/flutter_test.dart';
  54: import 'package:file/local.dart';
  55  ```

.fvm/flutter_sdk/dev/snippets/README.md:
    1: # Dartdoc Generation
    2  

    5  
    6: To generate these code blocks, Flutter uses dartdoc tools to turn documentation
    7  in the source code into API documentation, as seen on https://api.flutter.dev/.

   23  
   24: * A `dartpad` sample, which gets placed into a full-fledged application, and can
   25    be executed inline in the documentation on the web page using
   26:   DartPad.
   27  
   28  * A `sample`, which gets placed into a full-fledged application, but isn't
   29:   placed into DartPad in the documentation because it doesn't make sense to do
   30    so.
   31  
   32: Ideally, every sample is a DartPad sample, but some samples don't have any visual
   33  representation and some just don't make sense that way (for example, sample

   43  
   44: ```dart
   45  /// {@tool snippet}

   49  ///
   50: /// ```dart
   51  /// CircleAvatar(

   61  This uses the skeleton for [snippet](config/skeletons/snippet.html) snippets
   62: when generating the HTML to put into the Dart docs.
   63  

   65  
   66: The `../bots/analyze_sample_code.dart` script finds code inside the `@tool
   67: snippet` sections and uses the Dart analyzer to check them.
   68  

   91  
   92: ```dart
   93  // Examples can assume:

   98  You can assume that the entire Flutter framework and most common
   99: `dart:*` packages are imported and in scope; `dart:math` as `math` and
  100: `dart:ui` as `ui`.
  101  

  105  
  106: The code `sample` and `dartpad` tools can expand sample code into full Flutter
  107  applications. These sample applications can be directly copied and used to

  109  `flutter create` command to create a local project with the sample code. The
  110: `dartpad` samples are embedded into the API docs web page and are live
  111  applications in the API documentation.
  112  
  113: ```dart
  114  /// {@tool sample --template=stateless_widget_material}

  117  ///
  118: /// ```dart
  119  /// Widget build(BuildContext context) {

  142  
  143: The `sample` and `dartpad` tools also allow for quick Flutter app generation
  144  using the following command:

  154  To support showing an entire app when you click on the right tab of the
  155: code sample UI, we have to be able to insert the `sample` or `dartpad` block
  156  into the template and instantiate the right parts.

  159  contains a list of templates. These templates represent an entire app that the
  160: `sample` or `dartpad` can be placed into, basically a replacement for
  161: `lib/main.dart` in a flutter app package.
  162  

  167  
  168: The `../bots/analyze_sample_code.dart` script finds code inside the `@tool
  169: sample` sections and uses the Dart analyzer to check them after applying the
  170  specified template.

  173  
  174: A skeleton (concerning this tool) is an HTML template into which the Dart
  175  code blocks and descriptions are interpolated.

  178  [application](config/skeletons/sample.html) samples, one for
  179: [dartpad](config/skeletons/dartpad-sample.html), and one for
  180  [snippet](config/skeletons/snippet.html) code samples, but there could be more.

  187  The code block generation tools that process the source input and emit HTML for
  188: output, which dartdoc places back into the documentation. Any options given to
  189  the `{@tool ...}` directive are passed on verbatim to the tool.

  191  The `snippets` tool renders these examples through a combination of markdown
  192: and HTML using the `{@inject-html}` dartdoc directive.
  193  

  208  Note that generating the sample output will not allow you to run your code in
  209: DartPad, because DartPad pulls the code it runs from the appropriate docs server
  210  (master or stable).
  211  
  212: Copy the generated code and paste it into a regular DartPad instance to test if
  213: it runs in DartPad. To get the code that will be produced by your documentation
  214  changes, run sample analysis locally (see the next section) and paste the output
  215: into a DartPad at https://dartpad.dartlang.org.
  216  

  224  ```
  225: TMPDIR=/tmp bin/cache/dart-sdk/bin/dart dev/bots/analyze_sample_code.dart --temp=samples
  226  ```

  233  
  234: For example, the file `sample.src.widgets.animated_list.52.dart` points to the sample
  235: in `packages/flutter/src/widgets/animated_list.dart` at line 52. You can then take the
  236: contents of that file, and paste it into [Dartpad](https://dartpad.dev) and see if it
  237  works. If the sample relies on new features that have just landed, it may not work

.fvm/flutter_sdk/dev/snippets/config/.dartignore:
  1: This file makes the dev/bots/analyze.dart file ignore this directory.

.fvm/flutter_sdk/dev/snippets/config/templates/README.md:
   3  In general, creating application snippets can be accomplished with the following
   4: syntax inside of the dartdoc comment for a Flutter class/variable/enum/etc.:
   5  
   6: ```dart
   7  /// {@tool snippet --template=stateful_widget}

  10  /// above" or "see the code below", since the location of the description may
  11: /// change in the future. You can use dartdoc [Linking] in the description, and
  12  /// __Markdown__ too.
  13  ///
  14: /// ```dart preamble
  15  /// class Foo extends StatelessWidget {

  28  /// short version of the snippet code sample.
  29: /// ```dart
  30  /// String myValue = 'Foo';

  39  
  40: This will result in the template having the section that's inside "```dart"
  41  interpolated into the template's stateful widget's state object body.

  48  
  49: ```dart
  50: /// ```dart imports
  51: /// import 'package:flutter/rendering.dart';
  52  /// ```

  55  All code within a code block in a snippet needs to be able to be run through
  56: dartfmt without errors, so it needs to be valid code (This shouldn't be an
  57  additional burden, since all code will also be compiled to be sure it compiles).

  78    state variables. It also has a `preamble` in addition to the default code
  79:   block, which will be placed at the top level of the Dart file, so bare
  80    method calls are not allowed in the preamble. The default code block is

.fvm/flutter_sdk/dev/tools/gen_keycodes/README.md:
   2  
   3: This directory contains a keycode generator that can generate Dart code for
   4  the `LogicalKeyboardKey` and `PhysicalKeyboardKey` classes. It draws information

   7  
   8: It then generates `keyboard_key.dart` (containing the `LogicalKeyboardKey` and
   9: `PhysicalKeyboardKey` classes), and `keyboard_maps.dart`, containing
  10  platform-specific immutable maps for translating platform keycodes and

  21    names to Android keycode names (with the "KEY\_" prefix stripped off).
  22: - `data/keyboard_key.tmpl`: contains the template for the `keyboard_key.dart`
  23    file. Markers that begin and end with "@@@" denote the locations where
  24    generated data will be inserted.
  25: - `data/keyboard_maps.tmpl`: contains the template for the `keyboard_maps.dart`
  26    file. Markers that begin and end with "@@@" denote the locations where

  39  ```bash
  40: $FLUTTER_ROOT/bin/cache/dart-sdk/bin/dart bin/gen_keycodes.dart
  41  ```
  42  
  43: This will regenerate the `keyboard_key.dart` and `keyboard_maps.dart` files in
  44  place.

.fvm/flutter_sdk/packages/flutter/lib/src/foundation/README.md:
   1  The rule for packages in this directory is that they can depend on
   2: nothing but core Dart packages. They can't depend on `dart:ui`, they
   3  can't depend on any `package:`, and they can't depend on anything

   5  
   6: Currently they do depend on dart:ui, but only for `VoidCallback` and
   7  `hashValues` (and maybe one day `hashList` and `lerpDouble`), which
   8: are all intended to be moved out of `dart:ui` and into `dart:core`.
   9  

  11  
  12:  * https://github.com/dart-lang/sdk/issues/27791 (`VoidCallback`)
  13:  * https://github.com/dart-lang/sdk/issues/25217 (`hashValues`, `hashList`, and `lerpDouble`)

  11  /// Deferred components allow Flutter applications to download precompiled AOT
  12: /// dart code and assets at runtime, reducing the install size of apps and
  13  /// avoiding installing unnecessary code/assets on end user devices. Common

  20  /// Deferred components are currently an Android-only feature. The methods in
  21: /// this class are a no-op and all assets and dart code are already available
  22  /// without installation if called on other platforms.

  28    // TODO(garyq): We should eventually expand this to install components by loadingUnitId
  29:   // as well as componentName, but currently, loadingUnitId is opaque to the dart code
  30    // so this is not possible. The API has been left flexible to allow adding

  40    /// This method should be used for asset-only deferred components or loading just
  41:   /// the assets from a component with both dart code and assets. Deferred components
  42:   /// containing dart code should call `loadLibrary()` on a deferred imported
  43:   /// library's prefix to ensure that the dart code is properly loaded as
  44:   /// `loadLibrary()` will provide the loading unit id needed for the dart
  45    /// library loading process. For example:
  46    ///
  47:   /// ```dart
  48:   /// import 'split_component.dart' deferred as SplitComponent;
  49    /// ...

  52    ///
  53:   /// This method will not load associated dart libraries contained in the component,
  54    /// though it will download the files necessary and subsequent calls to `loadLibrary()`

  62    ///  * [uninstallDeferredComponent], a method to request the uninstall of a component.
  63:   ///  * [loadLibrary](https://api.dart.dev/dart-mirrors/LibraryDependencyMirror/loadLibrary.html),
  64:   ///    the dart method to trigger the installation of the corresponding deferred component that
  65:   ///    contains the dart library.
  66    static Future<void> installDeferredComponent({required String componentName}) async {

  82    ///

   18: /// received are decoded into Dart values. The [MessageCodec] used must be
   19  /// compatible with the one used by the platform plugin. This can be achieved

  107: /// received are decoded into Dart values. The [MethodCodec] used must be
  108  /// compatible with the one used by the platform plugin. This can be achieved

  110: /// platform side. The Dart type of arguments and results is `dynamic`,
  111  /// but only values supported by the specified [MethodCodec] can be used.

.fvm/flutter_sdk/packages/flutter_localizations/README.md:
  18  1. Add the new getter to the localizations class `MaterialLocalizations`,
  19:    in `flutter_localizations/lib/src/material_localizations.dart`.
  20  
  21  2. Implement a default value in `DefaultMaterialLocalizations` in
  22:    `flutter_localizations/lib/src/material_localizations.dart`
  23  
  24: 3. Add a test to `test/material/localizations_test.dart` that verifies that
  25     this new value is implemented.

  33     ```
  34:    dart dev/tools/localization/bin/gen_missing_localizations.dart
  35     ```

  38  
  39:    Finally you need to re-generate lib/src/l10n/localizations.dart by running:
  40     ```
  41:    dart dev/tools/localization/bin/gen_localizations.dart --overwrite
  42     ```

  60  
  61:    You also need to re-generate `lib/src/l10n/localizations.dart` by running:
  62     ```
  63:    dart dev/tools/localization/bin/gen_localizations.dart --overwrite
  64     ```

.fvm/flutter_sdk/packages/flutter_localizations/lib/flutter_localizations.dart:
   7  
   8: export 'src/cupertino_localizations.dart';
   9: export 'src/l10n/generated_cupertino_localizations.dart';
  10: export 'src/l10n/generated_material_localizations.dart';

   61  MaterialLocalizations class.

   75  with an '@' prefix. These '@' resources are not used by the generated
   76: Dart code at run time, they just exist to inform translators about how
   77  the value will be used, and to inform the code generator about what code

   22:   /// The dart libraries this component includes as listed in pubspec.yaml.

   24:   /// This list is only of dart libraries manually configured to be in this component.
   25    /// Valid libraries that are listed here will always be guaranteed to be

   33  
   34:   /// The minimal set of [LoadingUnit]s needed that contain all of the dart libraries in
   35    /// [libraries].
   36    ///
   37:   /// Each [LoadingUnit] contains the compiled code for a set of dart libraries. Each
   38:   /// [DeferredComponent] contains a list of dart libraries that must be included in the
   39    /// component. The set [loadingUnits] is all of the [LoadingUnit]s needed such that
   40:   /// all required dart libs in [libraries] are in the union of the [LoadingUnit.libraries]
   41    /// included by the loading units in [loadingUnits].

  108  /// Represents a single loading unit and holds information regarding it's id,
  109: /// shared library path, and dart libraries in it.
  110  class LoadingUnit {

    5: /// This file serves as the single point of entry into the `dart:io` APIs
    6  /// within Flutter tools.

    8  /// In order to make Flutter tools more testable, we use the `FileSystem` APIs
    9: /// in `package:file` rather than using the `dart:io` file APIs directly (see
   10: /// `file_system.dart`). Doing so allows us to swap out local file system
   11  /// access with mockable (or in-memory) file systems, making our tests hermetic

   14  /// We also use `package:platform` to provide an abstraction away from the
   15: /// static methods in the `dart:io` `Platform` class (see `platform.dart`). As
   16  /// such, do not export Platform from this file!

   18  /// To ensure that all file system and platform API access within Flutter tools
   19: /// goes through the proper APIs, we forbid direct imports of `dart:io` (via a
   20  /// test), forcing all callers to instead import this file, which exports the
   21: /// blessed subset of `dart:io` that is legal to use in Flutter tools.
   22  ///
   23  /// Because of the nature of this file, it is important that **platform and file
   24: /// APIs not be exported from `dart:io` in this file**! Moreover, be careful
   25  /// about any additional exports that you add to this file, as doing so will
   26  /// increase the API surface that we have to test in Flutter tools, and the APIs
   27: /// in `dart:io` can sometimes be hard to use in tests.
   28: import 'dart:async';
   29: import 'dart:io' as io

   830    static bool _isValidClassName(String className) {
   831:     // Public Dart class name cannot begin with an underscore
   832      if (className[0] == '_') {

   834      }
   835:     // Dart class name cannot contain non-alphanumeric symbols
   836      if (className.contains(RegExp(r'[^a-zA-Z_\d]'))) {

   838      }
   839:     // Dart class name must start with upper case character
   840      if (className[0].contains(RegExp(r'[a-z]'))) {

   842      }
   843:     // Dart class name cannot start with a number
   844      if (className[0].contains(RegExp(r'\d'))) {

   858        throw L10nException(
   859:         "The 'output-class', $classNameString, is not a valid public Dart class name.\n"
   860        );

   932    static bool _isValidGetterAndMethodName(String name) {
   933:     // Public Dart method name must not start with an underscore
   934      if (name[0] == '_') {

   936      }
   937:     // Dart getter and method name cannot contain non-alphanumeric symbols

   940      }
   941:     // Dart method name must start with lower case character

  1063:   /// Updates dart-defines based on [webRenderer].
  1064    @visibleForTesting
  1065:   static List<String> updateDartDefines(List<String> dartDefines, String webRenderer) {
  1066:     final Set<String> dartDefinesSet = dartDefines.toSet();
  1067:     if (!dartDefines.any((String d) => d.startsWith('FLUTTER_WEB_AUTO_DETECT='))
  1068:         && dartDefines.any((String d) => d.startsWith('FLUTTER_WEB_USE_SKIA='))) {
  1069:       dartDefinesSet.removeWhere((String d) => d.startsWith('FLUTTER_WEB_USE_SKIA='));

  41: // The "ExtraFrontEndOptions", "ExtraGenSnapshotOptions", and "DartDefines" cases are special cases
  42: // that we should remove; search for "useLegacyNames" in commands/assemble.dart and other files.
  43  // TODO(ianh): consider changing all underscores to hyphens in argument names when we can do aliases.
  44: // That depends on being able to have argument aliases: https://github.com/dart-lang/args/issues/181
  45: final RegExp _allowedArgumentNamePattern = RegExp(r'^([-a-z0-9_]+|ExtraFrontEndOptions|ExtraGenSnapshotOptions|DartDefines)$');

  176:     }, kDartDefines), <String>['true', 'false', 'flase']);

   42:   String dartPath;
   43    String constFinderPath;

   47    List<String> _getConstFinderArgs(String appDillPath) => <String>[
   48:     dartPath,
   49:     '--disable-dart-dev',
   50      constFinderPath,
   51      '--kernel-file', appDillPath,
   52:     '--class-library-uri', 'package:flutter/src/widgets/icon_data.dart',
   53      '--class-name', 'IconData',

   98

  385  
  386: /// A helper to create a Intellij Dart plugin jar.
  387  ///
  388  /// This jar contains META-INF/plugin.xml.
  389: /// Its contents were derived from the META-INF/plugin.xml from an Intellij Dart
  390  /// plugin installation.

  396  /// in another JAR.
  397: void createIntellijDartPluginJar(String pluginJarPath, FileSystem fileSystem) {
  398:   const String intellijDartPluginXml = r'''
  399  <idea-plugin version="2">
  400:   <name>Dart</name>
  401    <version>162.2485</version>

  403  
  404:   <description>Support for Dart programming language</description>
  405    <vendor>JetBrains</vendor>
  406    <depends>com.intellij.modules.xml</depends>
  407:   <depends optional="true" config-file="dartium-debugger-support.xml">JavaScriptDebugger</depends>
  408:   <depends optional="true" config-file="dart-yaml.xml">org.jetbrains.plugins.yaml</depends>
  409:   <depends optional="true" config-file="dart-copyright.xml">com.intellij.copyright</depends>
  410:   <depends optional="true" config-file="dart-coverage.xml">com.intellij.modules.coverage</depends>
  411  </idea-plugin>

  413  
  414:   final List<int> dartPluginBytes = utf8.encode(intellijDartPluginXml);
  415:   final Archive dartPlugins = Archive();
  416:   dartPlugins.addFile(ArchiveFile('META-INF/plugin.xml', dartPluginBytes.length, dartPluginBytes));
  417    fileSystem.file(pluginJarPath)
  418      ..createSync(recursive: true)
  419:     ..writeAsBytesSync(ZipEncoder().encode(dartPlugins));
  420  }

.fvm/flutter_sdk/packages/flutter_tools/test/integration.shard/README.md:
   4  they don't require actual devices, they run `flutter_tester` to test
   5: Dart VM and Flutter integration.
   6  

   9  ```shell
  10: ../../bin/cache/dart-sdk/bin/pub run test test/integration.shard
  11  ```
  12  
  13: You need to have downloaded the Dart SDK in your Flutter clone for this
  14  to work. Running `../../bin/flutter` will automatically download it.

   81: /// An event regarding the Dart VM.
   82  ///

   84  /// and contains the service port of the VM as well as a URL to connect to it.
   85: class DartVmEvent {
   86:   DartVmEvent._({required this.eventType, required this.servicePort, required this.uri});
   87  
   88:   /// The URL used to connect to the Dart VM.

   90

  103  /// This class can be connected to several instances of the Fuchsia device's
  104: /// Dart VM at any given time.
  105  class FuchsiaRemoteConnection {
  106    FuchsiaRemoteConnection._(this._useIpV6, this._sshCommandRunner)
  107:     : _pollDartVms = false;
  108  
  109:   bool _pollDartVms;
  110    final List<PortForwarder> _forwardedVmServicePorts = <PortForwarder>[];

  113  
  114:   /// A mapping of Dart VM ports (as seen on the target machine), to
  115    /// [PortForwarder] instances mapping from the local machine to the target
  116    /// machine.
  117:   final Map<int, PortForwarder> _dartVmPortMap = <int, PortForwarder>{};
  118  

  121  
  122:   /// A broadcast stream that emits events relating to Dart VM's as they update.
  123:   Stream<DartVmEvent> get onDartVmEvent => _onDartVmEvent;
  124:   late Stream<DartVmEvent> _onDartVmEvent;
  125:   final StreamController<DartVmEvent> _dartVmEventController =
  126:       StreamController<DartVmEvent>();
  127  
  128    /// VM service cache to avoid repeating handshakes across function
  129:   /// calls. Keys a URI to a DartVm connection instance.
  130:   final Map<Uri, DartVm?> _dartVmCache = <Uri, DartVm?>{};
  131  

  138  
  139:     Stream<DartVmEvent> dartVmStream() {
  140        Future<void> listen() async {
  141:         while (connection._pollDartVms) {
  142            await connection._pollVms();

  144          }
  145:         connection._dartVmEventController.close();
  146        }
  147  
  148:       connection._dartVmEventController.onListen = listen;
  149:       return connection._dartVmEventController.stream.asBroadcastStream();
  150      }
  151  
  152:     connection._onDartVmEvent = dartVmStream();
  153      return connection;

  163    /// Once this function is called, the instance of [FuchsiaRemoteConnection]
  164:   /// returned will keep all associated DartVM connections opened over the
  165    /// lifetime of the object.
  166    ///
  167:   /// At its current state Dart VM connections will not be added or removed over
  168    /// the lifetime of this object.

  226        // on the target before shutting down the forwarding itself.
  227:       final Uri uri = _getDartVmUri(pf);
  228:       final DartVm? vmService = _dartVmCache[uri];
  229:       _dartVmCache[uri] = null;
  230        await vmService?.stop();

  232      }
  233:     for (final PortForwarder pf in _dartVmPortMap.values) {

  406      String? addr;

  418:   /// Attempts to create a connection to a Dart VM.
  419    ///
  420    /// Returns null if either there is an [HttpException] or a
  421:   /// [TimeoutException], else a [DartVm] instance.
  422:   Future<DartVm?> _getDartVm(
  423      Uri uri, {
  424:     Duration timeout = _kDartVmConnectionTimeout,
  425    }) async {
  426:     if (!_dartVmCache.containsKey(uri)) {
  427        // When raising an HttpException this means that there is no instance of
  428:       // the Dart VM to communicate with.  The TimeoutException is raised when
  429:       // the Dart VM instance is shut down in the middle of communicating.
  430        try {
  431:         final DartVm dartVm = await DartVm.connect(uri, timeout: timeout);
  432:         _dartVmCache[uri] = dartVm;
  433        } on HttpException {

  440      }
  441:     return _dartVmCache[uri];
  442    }
